SIMPLE: pinnace
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Pinnace
<hw>Pin"nace</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>pinasse</ets>; cf. It. <ets>pinassa</ets>, <ets>pinazza</ets>, Sp.
<ets>pinaza</ets>; all from L. <ets>pinus</ets> a pine tree, anything
made of pine, e.g., a ship. Cf. <er>Pine</er> a tree.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<fld>(Naut.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A small vessel propelled by sails
or oars, formerly employed as a tender, or for coast defence; -- called
originally, <altname>spynace</altname> or
<altname>spyne</altname>.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>A man-of-war's
boat.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Whilst our <qex>pinnace</qex> anchors in the Downs.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A procuress; a pimp.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>B. Jonson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pinnacle</ent>⟦br⟧
